  {
    "id": "bank-a-q173",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "networking",
    "subtopic": "intrusion-detection",
    "stem": "What are the characteristics of stack based IDS?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "It is programmed to interpret a certain series of packets",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "It models the normal usage of the network as a noise characterization",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "They are integrated closely with the TCP/IP stack and watch packets",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "The host operating system logs in the audit information",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "explanation": "A stack-based IDS is hooked into the TCP/IP stack itself, so it inspects packets as they move up the layers and can drop them before the OS or application ever sees them. The distractors describe other IDS types: interpreting a series of packets is signature-based, modeling normal traffic as noise is anomaly-based, and reading OS audit logs is host-based.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 20
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "566b19f0177b1c6001aec229e8e477998be29c96"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q174",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "operating-systems",
    "subtopic": "file-systems",
    "stem": "The operating system keeps a small table containing information about all open files called ____________",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "file table",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "directory table",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "open-file table",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "system table",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "C"
    ],
    "explanation": "The OS keeps an open-file table holding an entry per currently open file (location on disk, access rights, open count), so it does not have to re-search the directory on every read or write. The directory structure on disk is separate; the in-memory table of open files is the open-file table.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 21
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "54e16477cdad295c39f6723d26758b1c27d7c4b3"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q175",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "operating-systems",
    "subtopic": "system-calls",
    "stem": "Whenever a process needs I/O to or from a disk it issues a ______________",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "system call to the operating system",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "a special procedure",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "system call to the CPU",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "all of the mentioned",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "A"
    ],
    "explanation": "Disk access is a privileged operation, so a user process cannot touch the controller directly. It issues a system call, which traps into kernel mode and lets the OS perform the transfer. \"System call to the CPU\" is nonsense: system calls are requests to the operating system, not to hardware.",
    "source": {
      "file": "exam noooow.pdf",
      "exam": "bank",
      "tier": "bank",
      "originalNumber": 22
    },
    "keyProvenance": "inline_bold",
    "keyVerified": true,
    "verificationLevel": "single",
    "needsReview": false,
    "flags": [],
    "dedupeHash": "8e03e25ea7f82c5f818e1a2d5d5493dd2f6e06f6"
  },
  {
    "id": "bank-a-q176",
    "type": "mcq",
    "topic": "operating-systems",
    "subtopic": "system-calls",
    "stem": "In Unix, which system call creates the new process?",
    "options": [
      {
        "label": "A",
        "text": "create",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "B",
        "text": "fork",
        "isCorrect": true
      },
      {
        "label": "C",
        "text": "new",
        "isCorrect": false
      },
      {
        "label": "D",
        "text": "none of the mentioned",
        "isCorrect": false
      }
    ],
    "answerOptionLabels": [
      "B"
    ],
    "explanation": "fork() is the Unix process-creation call: it duplicates the calling process, returning 0 in the child and the child's PID in the parent. exec() then replaces the child's image with a new program; there is no create() or new() system call in Unix.",
    "source": {
